{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"359c31e8-7c94-42e7-9c36-0c52911cb4ec","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, but I can answer your question directly — here's what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish as a **dotnet tool** on NuGet.org:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n1. **`PackAsTool=true`** — marks the project as a dotnet tool.\n2. **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI command users will run (e.g., `my-mcp-server`).\n3. **`OutputType=Exe`** — required for tools.\n\n### Publish workflow\n\n```bash\n# Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# Push (get your API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install & run with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server    # starts the stdio MCP server\n```\n\nDo you want me to create/update your `.csproj` file with these settings?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"22d0b821-9e17-42e1-87ba-6366bad8f44a","outputTokens":450,"requestId":"7013:33DFCD:14AC977:17E7B4C:69EC124A"},"id":"5f85cad3-a722-4968-b80e-86268d949c97","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:01:07.322Z","parentId":"f2b40651-fdb2-460d-bcf7-a495ae22e486"}
